## Example 5 — Real-World: Speed of Light Calculation

The speed of light is $3.0 \times 10^8$ m/s. The distance from the Sun to Earth is $1.5 \times 10^{11}$ m. How long does sunlight take to reach Earth?

### Step 1: Set Up the Division

$$\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Speed}} = \frac{1.5 \times 10^{11}}{3.0 \times 10^8}$$

### Step 2: Divide the Coefficients

$$\frac{1.5}{3.0} = 0.5$$

### Step 3: Subtract the Exponents

$$10^{11-8} = 10^3$$

### Step 4: Combine

$$\text{Time} = 0.5 \times 10^3 = 5.0 \times 10^2 \text{ seconds}$$

### Step 5: Convert to Meaningful Units

$$500 \text{ seconds} = 8 \text{ minutes and } 20 \text{ seconds}$$

### Step 6: Verify

$$5.0 \times 10^2 \times 3.0 \times 10^8 = 15.0 \times 10^{10} = 1.5 \times 10^{11} \checkmark$$

✅ Answer: Sunlight takes $5.0 \times 10^2$ seconds (about 8 minutes 20 seconds) to reach Earth.

